points of each connection share at least one active interface."}, {"#name": "simple-para", "$": {"id": "sp000010", "view": "all"}, "$$": [{"#name": "__text__", "_": "In this paper, we consider the standard matching problem in the context of multi-interface wireless networks. The aim is to maximize the number of parallel connections without incurring interferences. Given a network "}, {"#name": "math", "$": {"xmlns:mml": true, "altimg": "si1.gif", "display": "inline", "overflow": "scroll"}, "$$": [{"#name": "mi", "_": "G"}, {"#name": "mo", "_": "="}, {"#name": "mrow", "$$": [{"#name": "mo", "_": "("}, {"#name": "mi", "_": "V"}, {"#name": "mo", "_": ","}, {"#name": "mi", "_": "E"}, {"#name": "mo", "_": ")"}]}]}, {"#name": "__text__", "_": ", nodes "}, {"#name": "math", "$": {"xmlns:mml": true, "altimg": "si2.gif", "display": "inline", "overflow": "scroll"}, "$$": [{"#name": "mi", "_": "V"}]}, {"#name": "__text__", "_": " represent the devices, and edges "}, {"#name": "math", "$": {"xmlns:mml": true, "altimg": "si3.gif", "display": "inline", "overflow": "scroll"}, "$$": [{"#name": "mi", "_": "E"}]}, {"#name": "__text__", "_": " represent the connections that can be established. If node "}, {"#name": "math", "$": {"xmlns:mml": true, "altimg": "si4.gif", "display": "inline", "overflow": "scroll"}, "$$": [{"#name": "mi", "_": "x"}]}, {"#name": "__text__", "_": " participates in the communication with one of its neighbors by means of interface "}, {"#name": "math", "$": {"xmlns:mml": true, "altimg": "si5.gif", "display": "inline", "overflow": "scroll"}, "$$": [{"#name": "mi", "_": "i"}]}, {"#name": "__text__", "_": ", then another neighboring node of "}, {"#name": "math", "$": {"xmlns:mml": true, "altimg": "si6.gif", "display": "inline", "overflow": "scroll"}, "$$": [{"#name": "mi", "_": "x"}]}, {"#name": "__text__", "_": " can establish a connection (but not with "}, {"#name": "math", "$": {"xmlns:mml": true, "altimg": "si7.gif", "display": "inline", "overflow": "scroll"}, "$$": [{"#name": "mi", "_": "x"}]}, {"#name": "__text__", "_": ") only if it makes use of interface "}, {"#name": "math", "$": {"xmlns:mml": true, "altimg": "si8.gif", "display": "inline", "overflow": "scroll"}, "$$": [{"#name": "mi", "_": "j"}, {"#name": "mo", "_": "\u2260"}, {"#name": "mi", "_": "i"}]}, {"#name": "__text__", "_": ". The size of a solution for an instance of the outcoming matching problem, which we call "}, {"#name": "italic", "_": "Maximum Matching in Multi-Interface"}, {"#name": "__text__", "_": " networks ("}, {"#name": "italic", "_": "MMMI"}, {"#name": "__text__", "_": " for short), is always in between the sizes of the solutions for the same instance with respect to the standard matching and its induced version problems. However, we prove that "}, {"#name": "italic", "_": "MMMI"}, {"#name": "__text__", "_": " is "}, {"#name": "italic", "_": "NP"}, {"#name": "__text__", "_": "-hard even for proper interval graphs and for bipartite graphs of maximum degree "}, {"#name": "math", "$": {"xmlns:mml": true, "altimg": "si9.gif", "display": "inline", "overflow": "scroll"}, "$$": [{"#name": "mi", "_": "\u0394"}, {"#name": "mo", "_": "\u2265"}, {"#name": "mn", "_": "3"}]}, {"#name": "__text__", "_": ". We also show polynomially solvable cases of "}, {"#name": "italic", "_": "MMMI"}, {"#name": "__text__", "_": " with respect to different assumptions."}]}]}]}]}}